# Mind-body-exercise-affects-attention-switching-and-sustained-attention-in-female-adults-with
**Autores**: Not specified
**Año**: 2022
**Journal**: Scientific Paper
**DOI/Link**: N/A

## Abstract
Abstract
Since few studies have explored the impact of Pilates exercise on cognitive functions in adults with Attention Deficit/Hyper-
activity Disorder (ADHD), this study aims to evaluate the effect of Pilates training on attention switching and sustained 
attention in a sample of adults with ADHD. The sample consisted of 52 adults with ADHD in the age range of 20 to 50 years, 
who were randomized into a 24-week Pilates training group (n = 25) and a control group (n = 27). The participants were 
followed up for 6 months. The treatment group (Pilates exercise) exhibited significant improvement in sustained attention 
in the post-test and follow-up, particularly in terms of omission errors, commission errors, and reaction time (p < 0.05). 
Moreover, the

## Key Findings
Discussion
Given the paucity of research on the effect of Pilates exer-
cise on cognitive functions of adults with ADHD, this 
paper aims to investigate the effect of Pilates training exer-
cise on sustained and attention switching. According to the 
ANS deficit hypothesis of ADHD (Griffiths et al., 2017), 
cognitive deficits associated with this disorder are related 
to abnormal ANS function and arousal dysregulation. 
Despite the promising implications of mind-body exercises 
for psychological disorders, they have rarely been applied 
to ADHD. To the best of our knowledge, this is the first 
study to investigate the effect of Pilates training exercise 
on attentional function in individuals with ADHD, includ-
ing sustained and attention switching.
As regards attention switching, the results of the Wis-
consin card-sorting test for the Pilates group showed a 
significant drop in total errors in the post-test. The num-
ber of non-perseverative errors indicates errors commit-
ted by eac... (Extracted from Discussion)

## Methodology
Methods
Participants
Fifty-two female adults, who were blind to the objectives of 
the exercise, participated in this study, of whom 25% were 
aged 20 to 30 years, 45% were 30 to 40 years old, and 30% 
Current Psychology	
1 3
were 40 to 50 years old. Given the extended age range of 
participants (20–50), the effect of aging on key measures 
could be documented over the adult life span. Also, due to 
the known gender differences in attentional mechanism, 
only female participants were included in this study (Clarke 
et al., 2001). Participants were recruited from a private 
and a public center for adolescents and adults with ADHD 
via flyers and word of mouth. Inclusion criteria were 20 
to 50 years of age, meeting the Diagnostic and Statistical 
Manual of Mental Disorder-5 criteria for ADHD, an intel-
ligence quotient ≥80 and Conners Adult ADHD Rating 
Scale-self-report (CAARS) ≥ 65 (Conners et al., 1999) for 
either hyperactive-impulsive and inattentive symptoms, total 
DSM-V symptoms subscale, or ADHD index. The exclusion 
criteria were the inability to attend training sessions and 
regular physical activities, i.e., 30 min of exercise at least 
3 times a week, prior to the program (including individual 
and organized sports and leisure activities). Participants 
who were on medication for chronic diseases like diabetes 
II or high blood pressure were not excluded from the study. 
The details are outlined in Table 1. The sample size (n = 60) 
was determined using One-Sample T-Test Power Analysis 
and the effect size reported in a previous on the effect of 
Pilates exercise on different aspects of executive function 
(i.e., power = 0.85, Cohen’s d = 0.8, and alpha = 0.05 (Jura-
kic et al., 2017). During the study, three participants were 
omitted from the control group due to the intake of nerv-
ous system stimulant medication. Moreover, five adults in 
the experimental group were removed due to the failure to 
attend Pilates training sessions. Overall, 52 adults managed 
to complete the intervention (n = 27 in the control group, 
and n = 25 in the Pilates group). The power of the test was 
estimated at 0.80.
Procedure
The study was undertaken according to the Helsinki Dec-
laration in strict observance of the guidelines stipulated 
by the Institutional Review Board and Ethics Committee 
of Bioethics at the Ferdowsi University of Mashhad (Reg-
istration code: IR UM.REC.1398.133). The prescreening 
was conducted over the phone for 74 potential subjects 
of whom 68 were asked to attend the in-person screen-
ing. The participants who had received Pilates training or 
cognitive behavioral therapy for ADHD over the last two 
years (n = 3) and those with a confirmed diagnosis of any 
disorders other than ADHD (n = 4) were excluded in this 
stage. Of 68 subjects asked to attend the in-person screen-
ing, eight did not meet the diagnostic criteria for ADHD, 
had an IQ level ≤ 80, and exercised regularly. Finally, 
60 participants were recruited. Informed consent was 
obtained before participation and subjects were assured 
they could withdraw from the study at any stage. After the 
baseline measurements, they were randomized into either 
the experimental (n = 30) or control (n = 30) groups. Fig-
ure 1 shows sample requirements. A clinical psychologist 
with a Ph.D. degree supervised all diagnostic and screen-
ing measures. During the screening visit, the participant’s 
demographic information, records of medical and psy-
chiatric treatments and informed consents were obtained. 
