The short form of the Wechsler Adult Intelligence Scale 
was employed to assess IQ levels. Also, the diagnostic 
criteria of ADHD were measured using Conner’s Adult 
Diagnostic Interview for DSM-5. The treatment responses 
were evaluated using the continuous performance task and 
Wisconsin Card Sorting Test at three points: 2 weeks pre-
intervention, post-intervention, and at 6-month follow-up. 
The initial screening, baseline evaluation, intervention and 
6-month follow-up were conducted at the laboratory. The 
tests were run at 10-min intervals. The intervention group 
received Pilates training for 24 weeks, 3 times a week, 
each lasting for 45 min. Moreover, participants in the 
experimental group were requested not to perform Pilates 
training individually during the six-month follow-up. In 
line with the previous research on treating adults with 
ADHD, feasibility was set to a maximum of 25% attrition 
and over 75% attendance. Moreover, the response rate of 
participants to the questionnaire, which was adapted from 
Bramham et al. (2009), was considered as the indication 
of treatment acceptance. In this inventory, a rating of 7 
suggests the highest level of satisfaction with treatment 
(Bramham et al., 2009). In the Pilates training group, 25 
participants complete the intervention, attending 69.83 
(SD = 2. 20) out of 72 sessions. Based on the treatment 
acceptability questionnaire (range of 1–7, where 7 sug-
gests the highest consent), the treatment was overall 
accepted by participants (M = 6.1, SD = 0.36). At the end 
of the research, the participants were acknowledged by 
some gifts.
Pilates Training
The Contemporary Pilates method utilized in the experimen-
tal group consists of specific exercises that are performed 
on mats and require body awareness, strength, stretching 
and balance. The Pilates exercises were carried out 8–10 
times for 2–3 sets. The intensity of exercises was increased 
if they were easy for participants. In addition, exercises were 
commenced at level one and gradually augmented to level 
three (level one consists of a simple version of exercises 
compared to level three, which is the hardest one). Each 
session comprises 15 min warm-up, 25–45 min Pilates exer-
cises and 10 min cool-down. Four different positions were 
practiced in Pilates exercises, including supine, side-lying, 
prone, and sitting positions. The training was conducted 
three times a week for over 24 weeks. In the first month, 
exercises were meant to boost general fitness. The training 
focused on building up flexibility in the second month and 
boosting strength in the third month. The next three months 
integrated flexibility, stretching and strength (Seghatoleslami 
et al., 2018). One physical coach with at least five years of 
