experience in Pilates training led the intervention program. 
The pre-existing treatment was constant in participants in 
the control group during the 24-week intervention and they 
were offered the Pilates training after follow-up.
Measures
Attention Switching  The Wisconsin Card Sorting Test 
(WCST; Grant & Berg, 1948) was originally developed to 
assess abstract reasoning and the ability to switch cognitive 
strategies in response to environmental changes. The test 
draws on stimulus and response cards that display various 
forms in diverse colors and numbers. The 128-card comput-
erized version of the WCST requires participants to sort out 
cards according to diverse principles (i.e., by color, form, 
or number) using four number keys on the laptop keyboard. 
After each sorting, the participant receives feedback in form 
of “right or wrong” on the screen. The rules change after 
10 correct sorting. The perseverative error index has been 
shown to be the chief outcome of executive function meas-
urement in which participants provide a response based on 
a wrong sorting rule (Zhang et al., 2018). Previous research 
on WCST has presented demographically corrected nor-
mative data from 899 subjects in the age range of 6.5 to 
89 years, which provides essential interpretive and diag-
nostic guidelines. Reliability and validity information is 
also included along with data on children and adolescent 
populations. In the present study, a Cronbach Alpha of .85 
was considered.
Sustained Attention  A Continuous Performance Task (CPT; 
Cornoldi et al., 1991) is one of several neuropsychological 
tests utilized to assess one’s selective and sustained atten-
tion. For the CPT, the participant is asked to sit behind a 
computer and his/her ability to remain seated, allocate atten-
tion and constrain impulsivity is assessed over time. The 
participant is then instructed to press a button in response 
to specific geometric shapes that appear on the screen. Par-
ticipants aged 12–60 years performed a more challenging 
cognitive task, in which they needed to press a button when 
the symbol of a resembling color and shape re-emerged on 
the screen. At the end of the test, a comparison was drawn 
with the results obtained from the age and gender-adjusted 
reference group. Despite some variations in scoring, there 
are four primary scores in these tests.
Reaction times: It measures the time interval between the 
presentation of a stimulus and the participant’s response.
Omission errors: This indicates the number of times a 
target appears, but the participant fails to respond/click 
on the mouse. A high omission rate denotes the subject 
is either not paying sufficient attention (distractibility) to 
the stimulus or produces a delayed response.
Commission errors: It indicates the number of times 
a participant responds without a target appearing on 
the screen. A fast reaction time with a high commis-
sion error signals impulsivity while a slow reaction 
time with high commission and omission errors sug-
gests general inattention (White et al., 2017). In this 
version of CPT, the test-retest reliability coefficients 
for various measures were reported to be in the range 
of.59 and .93 in a study on primary school students in 
Iran. Also, the criterion validity coefficients for the CPT 
were measured and validated in children (Hadianfard 
et al., 2001). In the present study, a Cronbach Alpha of 
.82 was considered.
Data Analysis
Data analysis was conducted using the R statistical software 
version 3.6.3. Mean and SD were calculated for each par-
ticipant based on descriptive statistics. A 2 × 3 mixed-model 
multivariate analysis of variance (MANCOVA) was used 
for both groups (Pilates training and the control) at differ-
ent stages (pretest and posttest, and follow-up) and age was 
treated as a covariate. Whenever the interaction of time and 
groups was significant, the adjusted Bonferroni post hoc 
test was utilized to investigate significant differences. In all 
tests, a significant level of >.05 was considered Also, the 
effect size was computed as d = M change score training group – M 
change score control group / SD pooled.
