## Results
results suggested that attention switching improved substantially in the post-test in terms of perseverative 
errors, non-perseverative errors, and total errors (p < 0.05). Findings offer evidence on the positive impact of Pilates training 
on attention problems in adults with ADHD.
Registration code: IR.UM. REC.1398.133.
Keywords  Attention-Deficit/Hyperactivity Disorder · Pilates · Mind-body exercise · Sustained attention · Attention 
switching
Attention Deficit/Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD) is prob-
ably the most common neurodevelopmental disorder in 
children (Wilmshurst, 2014), which is characterized by 
behavioral symptoms such as inattention, hyperactivity, and 
impulsiveness (Asherson, 2012). About 2.5% of the adult 
population demonstrate the criteria that are typical of ADHD 
(Volkow & Swanson, 2013). ADHD is characterized by vari-
ous deficits within the cognitive domains such as attention 
(Barkley, 1997), inhibitory control (Rubia et al., 2005), 
working memory (Kasper et al., 2012), and executive func-
tions (EFs) (Hudec et al., 2015), which are more coherent 
and discriminant predictors of ADHD in adulthood than the 
symptoms of inattention and hyperactive impulses (Kessler 
et al., 2010). In individuals with ADHD, cognitive deficits 
embrace impaired attentional, timing, inhibitory, and moti-
vational control (Smith et al., 2006), as well as emotional 
dysregulation (Kessler et al., 2010). These impairments are 
most commonly associated with sustained and attention 
switching (Borella et al., 2013; Mueller et al., 2017). Sus-
tain attention represents the ability to continuously complete 
a task over an extended period of time without significant 
performance loss (Oken et al., 2006). Attention switching 
is also defined as the capacity to toggle between tasks with-
out a remarkable loss of performance (Vijayraghavan et al., 
2007). Musser et al. (2011) revealed that ADHD in children 
is linked to abnormal parasympathetic mechanisms related 
to the emotion regulation (Musser et al., 2011). The inability 
of the Autonomic Nervous System (ANS) to react to recent 
developments in environmental demands may increase dis-
traction by irrelevant stimuli and/or undermine one’s ability 
to identify proper stimuli. Thus, failure to maintain atten-
tion or behavioral disinhibition, which is usually observed in 
ADHD, is also associated with ANS dysregulation (Griffiths 
