Current Psychology
1 3
et al., 2017). It is suggested that sustained attention may 
depend upon the level of arousal (Oken et al., 2006). While 
methylphenidate hydrochloride is recommended as a first-
line therapy for the main symptoms of ADHD, there are 
limits to the psychopharmacologic treatment of methylphe-
nidate, non-response, contraindications, adverse reactions 
or preference of patients for non-pharmacological treatment.
The cognitive performance of children and adults with 
ADHD can be improved by aerobic exercise (Cerrillo-
Urbina et al., 2015; Chan et al., 2021; Ng et al., 2017; Rasso-
vsky & Alfassi, 2019). Also, like physical activities, mind-
body exercises are linked to the transient mental state of 
consciousness through self-directed mental attention (Ralph 
La Forge, 1997). This inner reflection and meticulousness 
are distinctive characteristics that set it apart from routine 
body-centered oxygen consumption or solid workouts (Kim 
et al., 2012). A mind-body centered approach is reliant on 
the activation of inner energy. It also nurtures self-manage-
ment and self-control by accounting for interception and 
respiratory sensations characterized by low-intensity physi-
cal movements (Jeon & Lee, 2007). Mind-body exercise 
raises participants’ awareness of the connection between 
mind, body and emotions, which in turn improves their 
ability to tackle detrimental mental states (Schure et al., 
2008). Mind-body therapy covers biofeedback, mindful-
ness, progressive relaxation, deep breathing, hypnother-
apy, guided imagery, yoga and Pilates, among other things 
(McClafferty, 2011). Bachmann et al. (2018) documented 
significant improvement in the activation of the right pari-
etal lobe (the bilateral inferior parietal lobule, the right pos-
terior insula and the right precuneus) in working memory 
tasks in the mindfulness-training group. Moreover, they 
reported a substantial reduction in self-rated ‘Inattention/
Memory Problems’ following mindfulness training, which 
was associated with stronger activation in parts of the left 
putamen, globus pallidus and thalamus (Bachmann et al., 
2018). In another study, Mitchell et al. (2017) reported 
that group-based mindfulness therapy for 8 weeks had a 
substantial positive impact on self-reported EF and ADHD 
symptoms (based on laboratory and ecological momentary 
evaluation). However, no improvement was observed in EF 
tasks including Attention Network Task - a computerized 
test that evaluates alertness (maintaining an observant state 
of readiness), conflict (prioritization of competing tasks), 
and orientation (selection of a single stimulus out of sev-
eral inputs) - the Trail Making Test (which examines inhi-
bition and attentional set-shifting), the Digit Span Test (as 
a measure of working memory) and Conners’ Continuous 
Performance Test (as a criterion for response inhibition) 
(Mitchell et al., 2017).
In recent years, Pilates has been presented as an effective 
mind-body exercise. Originally espoused by Joseph Pilates 
throughout the 20s, Pilates involves floor-based activities 
that require specialized instrumentation. The main compo-
nents of Pilates are breathing, core stability, flexibility, mus-
cle control, mind-body connection, posture, and strength 
(Wells et al., 2012). Particularly, since the core idea behind 
Pilates is body management by the mind, it falls in the cat-
egory of mind-body exercise. Moreover, Pilates breathing 
style increases concentration and relaxation and prepares 
the body to perform movements under optimal conditions 
(Lim & Yoon, 2017). In addition, a structural-model study 
indicates that Pilates, due to its restful impact on the body, 
can regulate attention mechanisms (Memmedova, 2015). 
There is ample evidence that individuals with ADHD suf-
fer from arousal regulation. Thus, impaired arousal regula-
tion in ADHD leads to reduced precision, slow response 
speed and increased reaction time (Kara et al., 2013). 
Proper arousal-modulation results in inflated potency in 
performing tasks that require attention, which could be 
seen as a prelude to information processing (Petersen & 
Posner, 2012). In addition, research shows that twenty-
four 60-min sessions of Pilates training can significantly 
improve visuospatial/executive, attention, language, 
abstracting, delayed recall, and orientation in the elderly 
with mild cognitive impairments (Jurakic et al., 2017). 
According to another study, Pilates training can improve 
the reaction time of the elderly (Mello et al., 2018). The 
existing body of literature offers evidence on the efficacy 
of Pilates training in cognitive skills. Compared to other 
mind-body training approaches, scant scholarly attention 
has been paid to the interventional impacts of Pilates on 
psychiatric disorders’ symptoms. It is not clear, however, 
whether this mind-body training can be effective for adults 
with ADHD. The positive results of the mind-body exer-
cise in the psychological disorder have been documented 
but the effect of Pilate’s training on cognitive skills, espe-
cially on cognitive skills of adults with ADHD, has rarely 
been studied. In light of these findings, it is hypothesized 
that Pilates intervention can affect sustained and attention 
switching in individuals with ADHD. Hence, the main 
goal of this study is to explore the effect of Pilates training 
on attention switching and sustained attention in female 
adults with ADHD. The secondary aim of this study is to 
investigate the lasting effect of Pilates training on attention 
switching and sustained attention of adults with ADHD 
after six months.
Material and

## Clinical Significance
Conclusion
This study offered evidence on the impact that Pilates train-
ing on adult ADHD. As such, it helped overcome some limi-
tations outlined in the previous studies, like the inclusion of 
a comparison-control group, restriction of intervention to 
Pilates training, the prevention of other treatment modali-
ties, and selection of a sample consisting of only adults with 
ADHD. In keeping with the literature, the findings suggest 
the high potential of Pilates training as an intervention to 
foster cognitive abilities in adults with ADHD.
